<H3><A name=3Dthink>Things to Think About</A></H3>
<P>
<P>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B>Oral Communication is different from written communication</B>
  <P>Listeners have one chance to hear your talk and can't "re-read" =
when they=20
  get confused. In many situations, they have or will hear several talks =
on the=20
  same day. Being clear is particularly important if the audience can't =
ask=20
  questions during the talk. There are two well-know ways to communicate =
your=20
  points effectively. The first is to K.I.S.S. (keep it simple stupid). =
Focus on=20
  getting one to three key points across. Think about how much you =
remember from=20
  a talk last week. Second, repeat key insights: tell them what you're =
going to=20
  tell them (Forecast), tell them, and tell them what you told them =
(Summary).
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Think about your audience</B>
  <P>Most audiences should be addressed in layers: some are experts in =
your=20
  sub-area, some are experts in the general area, and others know little =
or=20
  nothing. Who is most important to you? Can you still leave others with =

  something? For example, pitch the body to experts, but make the =
forecast and=20
  summary accessible to all.
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Think about your rhetorical goals</B>
  <P>For conference talks, for example, I recommend two rhetorical =
goals: leave=20
  your audience with a clear picture of the gist of your contribution, =
and make=20
  them want to read your paper. Your presentation should not replace =
your paper,=20
  but rather whet the audience appetite for it. Thus, it is commonly =
useful to=20
  allude to information in the paper that can't be covered adequately in =
the=20
  presentation. Below I consider goals for <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://pages.cs.wisc.edu/~markhill/conference-talk.html#interview=
">academic=20
  interview talks</A> and <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://pages.cs.wisc.edu/~markhill/conference-talk.html#other">cl=
ass=20
  presentations.</A>
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Practice in public</B>
  <P>It is hard distilling work down to 20 or 30 minutes.
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Prepare</B>
  <P>See David Patterson's <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://pages.cs.wisc.edu/~markhill/conference-talk.html#badtalk">=
How to=20
  Give a Bad Talk</A>=20
  <P></P></LI></OL>
