<H3><A name=3Doutline>A Generic Conference Talk Outline</A></H3>
<P>This conference talk outline is a starting point, not a rigid =
template. Most=20
good speakers average two minutes per slide (not counting title and =
outline=20
slides), and thus use about a dozen slides for a twenty minute =
presentation.=20
<UL>
  <LI><B>Title/author/affiliation</B> (1 slide)=20
  <LI><B>Forecast</B> (1 slide)<BR>Give gist of problem attacked and =
insight=20
  found (What is the one idea you want people to leave with? This is the =

  "abstract" of an oral presentation.)=20
  <LI><B>Outline</B> (1 slide)<BR>Give talk structure. Some speakers =
prefer to=20
  put this at the bottom of their title slide. (Audiences like =
predictability.)=20
  <LI><B>Background</B>=20
  <UL>
    <LI><B>Motivation and Problem Statement</B> (1-2 slides)<BR>(Why =
should=20
    anyone care? Most researchers overestimate how much the audience =
knows about=20
    the problem they are attacking.)=20
    <LI><B>Related Work</B> (0-1 slides)<BR>Cover superficially or omit; =
refer=20
    people to your paper.=20
    <LI><B>Methods</B> (1 slide)<BR>Cover quickly in short talks; refer =
people=20
    to your paper. </LI></UL>
  <LI><B>Results</B> (4-6 slides)<BR>Present key results and key =
insights. This=20
  is main body of the talk. Its internal structure varies greatly as a =
function=20
  of the researcher's contribution. (Do not superficially cover all =
results;=20
  cover key result well. Do not just present numbers; interpret them to =
give=20
  insights. Do not put up large tables of numbers.)=20
  <LI><B>Summary</B> (1 slide)=20
  <LI><B>Future Work</B> (0-1 slides)<BR>Optionally give problems this =
research=20
  opens up.=20
  <LI><B>Backup Slides</B> (0-3 slides)<BR>Optionally have a few slides =
ready=20
  (not counted in your talk total) to answer expected questions. (Likely =

  question areas: ideas glossed over, shortcomings of methods or =
results, and=20
  future work.) </LI></UL>
<H3><A name=3Dinterview>Academic Interview Talks</A></H3>
<P>The rhetorical goal for any interview talk is very different than a=20
conference talk. The goal of a conference talk is to get people =
interested in=20
your paper and your work. The goal of an interview talk is to get a job, =
for=20
which interest in your work is one part.=20
<P>There are two key audiences for an academic interview talk, and you =
have to=20
reach both. One is the people in your sub-area, who you must impress =
with the=20
depth of your contribution. The other is the rest of the department, who =
you=20
must get to understand your problem, why it is important, and a =
hand-wave at=20
what you did. Both audiences will evaluate how well you speak as an=20
approximation of how well you can teach.=20
<P>An algorithm:=20
<UL>
  <LI>Take a 20-minute conference talk.=20
  <LI>Expand the 5 minute introduction to 20 minutes to drive home the =
problem,=20
  why it's important, and the gist of what you've done.=20
  <LI>Do the rest of the conference talk, minus the summary and future =
work.=20
  <LI>Add 10 minutes of deeper stuff from your thesis (to show your =
depth). It=20
  is okay lose people outside of your sub-area (as long as you get them =
back in=20
  the next bullet).=20
  <LI>Do the summary and future work from the conference talk in a =
manner=20
  accessible to all.=20
  <LI>Add 10 ten minutes to survey all the other stuff you have done (to =
show=20
  your breadth).=20
  <LI>Save 5 minutes for questions (to show that you are organized). =
</LI></UL>
<H3><A name=3Dother>Other Talks</A></H3>Other talks should be prepared =
using the=20
same principles of considering audience and rhetorical purpose. A =
presentation=20
on a project in a graduate class, for example, seeks to reach the =
professor=20
first and fellow students second. Its purpose is to get a good grade by=20
impressing people that a quality project was done. Thus, methods should =
be=20
described in must more detail than for a conference talk.=20
