<P><FONT size=3D6>
<CENTER><B><A name=3Dbadtalk>How to Give a Bad Talk</A></B>
<P></FONT><FONT size=3D4>David A. Patterson
<P>Computer Science Division<BR>University of California-Berkeley
<P>Circa 1983 </FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<P>Ten commandments (with annotations gleaned from Patterson's talk by =
Mark D.=20
Hill):=20
<OL type=3DI>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not be neat</B>
  <P>Why waste research time preparing slides? Ignore spelling, grammar =
and=20
  legibility. Who cares what 50 people think?
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not waste space</B>
  <P>Transparencies are expensive. If you can save five slides in each =
of four=20
  talks per year, you save $7.00/year!
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not covet brevity</B>
  <P>Do you want to continue the stereotype that engineers can't write? =
Always=20
  use complete sentences, never just key words. If possible, use whole=20
  paragraphs and read every word.
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt cover thy naked slides</B>
  <P>You need the suspense! Overlays are too flashy.
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not write large</B>
  <P>Be humble -- use a small font. Important people sit in front. Who =
cares=20
  about the riff-raff?
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not use color</B>
  <P>Flagrant use of color indicates uncareful research. It's also =
unfair to=20
  emphasize some words over others.
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not illustrate</B>
  <P>Confucius says ``<I>A picture =3D 10K words</I>,'' but Dijkstra =
says=20
  ``<I>Pictures are for weak minds.</I>'' Who are you going to believe? =
Wisdom=20
  from the ages or the person who first counted goto's?
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not make eye contact</B>
  <P>You should avert eyes to show respect. Blocking screen can also add =

mystery.
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not skip slides in a long talk</B>
  <P>You prepared the slides; people came for your whole talk; so just =
talk=20
  faster. Skip your summary and conclusions if necessary.
  <P></P>
  <LI><B>Thou shalt not practice</B>
  <P>Why waste research time practicing a talk? It could take several =
hours out=20
  of your two years of research. How can you appear spontaneous if you =
practice?=20
  If you do practice, argue with any suggestions you get and make sure =
your talk=20
  is longer than the time you have to present it.
  <P></P></LI></OL>
<P>Commandment X is most important. <I>Even if you break the other nine, =
this=20
one can save you.</I> </P></BODY></HTML>
